tools_called.args:
{"query": "To control Crassula helmsii, how do chemical methods like herbicides compare in effectiveness to physical methods like using lightproof barriers or salt water?", "summary": "Chemical methods, particularly herbicides, show variable effectiveness. Seven studies found that glyphosate reduced C. helmsii, with one study showing 98% reduction when combined with diquat, and another achieving 80% reduction when covering with carpet before glyphosate treatment. Three out of four studies found that diquat or diquat alginate reduced or eradicated submerged C. helmsii, while one study found no effect. Treatment with dichlobenil and terbutryne showed partial reductions in biomass in controlled trials, but one field study found no effect from dichlobenil. Hydrogen peroxide was found to be ineffective according to one controlled study.

Physical methods show different effectiveness results. Lightproof barriers (black sheeting or carpet strips) were effective in five before-and-after studies, eradicating or severely reducing C. helmsii cover, although progressive recolonization occurred at two sites. Salt water was highly effective, with two replicated controlled container trials and two field trials finding that seawater eradicated C. helmsii. There is currently no evidence available for the effects of manual or mechanical control methods.

The combination of physical and chemical methods shows promise, with one study finding that covering C. helmsii with carpet followed by glyphosate treatment killed 80% of the plant.", "action_ids": ["1279", "1281", "1294", "1288", "1278", "1313", "1276"]}

