  "query": "What factors appear to influence the success of trapping as a control method for invasive crayfish?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the evidence found, several factors influence the success of trapping as a control method for invasive Procambarus crayfish. A controlled, replicated study from Italy found that baiting traps with food (tinned meat) was more effective than using male and female pheromones or no bait, with over half of all crayfish being caught in traps baited with food (Action ID 1029). A before-and-after study in Switzerland and a replicated, controlled study from Italy demonstrated that combining trapping with predator introduction was significantly more effective at reducing red swamp crayfish populations than trapping or predation alone (Action ID 1031).\n\nThe evidence also suggests that while trapping alone can be effective, integrated approaches appear to be more successful. However, no studies were found that directly tested the effects of removing or controlling non-native crayfish on overall ecosystem populations (Action ID 797).",
